SIMPLE: humor
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Humor
<hw>Hu"mor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>humour</ets>,
OF. <ets>humor</ets>, <ets>umor</ets>, F. <ets>humeur</ets>, L.
<ets>humor</ets>, <ets>umor</ets>, moisture, fluid, fr.
<ets>humere</ets>, <ets>umere</ets>, to be moist. See
<er>Humid</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also <asp>humour</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Moisture, especially, the moisture or fluid of animal
bodies, as the chyle, lymph, etc.; <as>as, the <ex>humors</ex> of the
eye, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ancient physicians believed that there were four
humors (the blood, phlegm, yellow bile or choler, and black bile or
melancholy), on the relative proportion of which the temperament and
health depended.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A vitiated or morbid animal fluid,
such as often causes an eruption on the skin.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A body full
of <xex>humors</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W. Temple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>State of mind, whether habitual or temporary (as
formerly supposed to depend on the character or combination of the
fluids of the body); disposition; temper; mood; <as>as, good
<ex>humor</ex>; ill <ex>humor</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Examine how your <qex>humor</qex> is inclined,⟦br⟧
And which the ruling passion of your mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prince of a pleasant <qex>humor</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I like not the <qex>humor</qex> of lying.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Changing and uncertain states of
mind; caprices; freaks; vagaries; whims.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is my friend all perfection, all virtue and discretion? Has he not
<qex>humors</qex> to be endured?</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That quality of the imagination which gives to ideas
an incongruous or fantastic turn, and tends to excite laughter or mirth
by ludicrous images or representations; a playful fancy;
facetiousness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For thy sake I admit⟦br⟧
That a Scot may have <qex>humor</qex>, I'd almost said wit.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A great deal of excellent <qex>humor</qex> was expended on the
perplexities of mine host.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Aqueous humor</b></col>, <col><b>Crystalline
humor</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Crystalline lens</b></col>,
<col><b>Vitreous humor</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Eye</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Out of humor</b></col>, <cd>dissatisfied;
displeased; in an unpleasant frame of mind.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Wit; satire; pleasantry; temper; disposition;
mood; frame; whim; fancy; caprice. See <er>Wit</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 713 --></p>

<p><ent>Humor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Humor
<hw>Hu"mor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Humored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Humoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To comply with the
humor of; to adjust matters so as suit the peculiarities, caprices, or
exigencies of; to adapt one's self to; to indulge by skillful
adaptation; <as>as, to <ex>humor</ex> the mind</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is my part to invent, and the musician's to <qex>humor</qex>
that invention.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To help on by indulgence or compliant treatment; to
soothe; to gratify; to please.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You <qex>humor</qex> me when I am sick.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To gratify; to indulge. See
<er>Gratify</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Humoral</ent>⟦br⟧
